# Sunset Horizon — Cursor Rules

You are working on Sunset Horizon, a static React + TypeScript web app hosted on GitHub Pages.

## Product goal

Calculate the real sunset time behind terrain, not the official flat-horizon sunset time.

## Non-negotiable constraints

- No backend.
- No Supabase.
- No user account.
- Use browser-side computation.
- Use localStorage first; IndexedDB only if needed for large local cache.
- Keep the app deployable to GitHub Pages.
- Never add secrets or private API keys.
- Do not invent IGN API parameters. Isolate IGN calls in one client so they can be corrected easily.

## Technical stack

- React
- TypeScript strict
- Vite
- Tailwind CSS
- Leaflet / React Leaflet
- Recharts
- SunCalc or Astronomy Engine
- Vitest

## Architecture rules

Put domain logic in pure modules:

- `features/solar`
- `features/terrain`
- `features/horizon`
- `lib/geo`
- `lib/storage`

Do not put calculation logic directly inside React components.

React components should orchestrate state and render UI only.

## Testing rules

Add unit tests for:

- distance computation;
- destination point from azimuth;
- apparent terrain angle;
- blocking sample selection;
- sunset crossing interpolation;
- storage serialization.

## UI rules

- Mobile-first.
- Dark theme.
- Large corrected sunset time.
- Always distinguish official sunset from terrain-corrected sunset.
- Always display uncertainty and data source.
- Include clear error states for geolocation and IGN failures.

## Safety rules

For geolocation:

- request user permission only from explicit action;
- show fallback manual selection if denied.

For external API:

- handle rate limits;
- debounce recalculations;
- avoid repeated calls on every minor state update.
